1 13. Bureau of Paid Family and Medical Leave; responsibilities of commissioner.
2 Except as otherwise provided in this subchapter, the Commissioner of Labor shall
3 administer this subchapter through the Bureau of Paid Family and Medical Leave. The
4 commissioner may employ persons, make expenditures, require reports, make
5 investigations, impose assessments, coordinate with other departments and bureaus and
6 take other actions the commissioner determines necessary or suitable to administer this
7 subchapter. The commissioner shall determine methods of operational procedures in
8 accordance with the provisions of this subchapter.
9 Sec. 7. 26 MRSA §850-C, sub-§2, as enacted by PL 2023, c. 412, Pt. AAA, §7, is
10 amended to read:
11 2. Determination of weekly benefit amount. The weekly benefit amount paid to
12 employees and an employee or self-employed individuals individual on family leave or
13 medical leave is calculated as follows: 65% of that employee's or self-employed
14 individual's average weekly wage.
15 A. The portion of the covered individual's average weekly wage that is equal to or less
16 than 50% of the state average weekly wage must be replaced at a rate of 90%; and
17 B. The portion of the covered individual’s average weekly wage that is more than 50%
18 of the state average weekly wage must be replaced at a rate of 66% up to the maximum
19 weekly benefit.
20 Sec. 8. 26 MRSA §850-D, sub-§2, as enacted by PL 2023, c. 412, Pt. AAA, §7, is
21 repealed and the following enacted in its place:
22 2. Filing of application. The filing of an application for family leave and medical
23 leave benefits is governed by this subsection.
24 A. An individual may file an application for family leave benefits or medical leave
25 benefits no more than 60 days before the anticipated start date of family leave and
26 medical leave.
27 B. An individual may file an application for family leave benefits no more than 15
28 days after the start date of family leave.
29 C. An individual may file an application for medical leave benefits no more than 30
30 days after the start date of medical leave. The administrator shall waive the 30-day
31 filing deadline for good cause.
32 The administrator shall institute forms and procedures that are not unduly burdensome to
33 an individual claiming benefits.
